text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Liturgical Signing%0a%0a:Author: nicholasm%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aASL has become increasingly accepted as a language for traditional religious ceremonies%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aDeaf people can experience religious liturgies as ostracizing due to the focus on verbal components and lack of integration in the community [1]. In the Roman Catholic tradition, this barrier is being gradually removed, and many American dioceses (ecclesiastical districts) maintain at least one priest who is able to offer the sacraments in American Sign Language (ASL).%0a%0aVernacular (non-Latin) languages have been permitted for liturgical use since the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s, and a list of official translations is maintained by the Vatican. Currently, this list only includes spoken languages, but unofficial translations are not invalid or strictly prohibited. One theologian at Regina Apostolorum in Rome has argued in favor of fully signed sacraments, recognizing ASL and other forms of sign language as full languages [2]. %0a%0aIn our own state, both the Diocese of Pittsburgh and Archdiocese of Philadelphia have begun wide-reaching efforts to include and reach out to their deaf communities. In Pittsburgh, St. Mary of the Mount church has priests simultaneously sign the mass in ASL and speak it in English [3]. In Philadelphia, there are several parishes with regularly scheduled ASL mass, and several more priests are being trained in ASL in seminary [4]. For some deaf Catholics, the traditional form of the Latin Mass—which typically uses more visual rather than auditory cues—is helpful because it allows both deaf and hearing parishioners to follow along without any significant changes for either experience[1].%0a%0aThese moves towards more inclusive liturgy and other sacraments is especially important as a sign of acceptance of ASL as a language equivalent to any spoken language by even one of the most far-reaching groups in the world, the Catholic Church.%0a%0aExample ASL mass: https://youtu.be/6kDiDerryFk %0a%0a[1] https://www.americamagazine.org/faith/2021/07/20/latin-mass-deaf-catholic-access-liturgy-241084 %0a[2] https://zenit.org/2019/03/05/sign-language-by-a-celebrant/%0a[3] https://www.post-gazette.com/local/city/2015/02/15/Signing-with-spirit-Pittsburgh-s-Catholic-Deaf-Community-gathers-at-St-Mary-of-the-Mount/stories/201501260158%0a[4] https://catholicphilly.com/2020/01/news/local-news/deaf-faithful-pray-the-mass-in-their-own-tongue-asl/ %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: F:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)%0a(:Title: Liturgical Signing:)
